  "history": {
  "historicalImportance": "Darbhanga has been the historical and cultural centre of the Mithila region. It was the seat of the Darbhanga Raj, one of the most influential zamindari estates in India, and has long been known for its contributions to education, Sanskrit learning and Maithili culture.",
  "formationHistory": "Darbhanga district was established on 1 January 1875 during the British administration. It later became the parent district from which several new districts, including Madhubani and Samastipur, were carved out.",
  "freedomMovement": "People of Darbhanga actively participated in India's freedom movement through the Non-Cooperation Movement, Civil Disobedience Movement and Quit India Movement. Many local leaders and students contributed to the struggle for independence.",
  "archaeologicalImportance": "Darbhanga is known for its ancient temples, palaces and historical structures associated with the Mithila civilization and the Darbhanga Raj.",
  "asiProtectedMonuments": [],
  "historicalTimeline": [
    "1 January 1875 - Darbhanga district was established.",
    "1947 - Darbhanga became part of the Indian state of Bihar after Independence.",
    "1972 - Samastipur district was carved out of Darbhanga district."
  ]
